snippet.textDisplay:
Whether he wants to be vaccinated or not, Novak Djokovic must have been aware that in order to be able to play in Australia he would need to be double vaccinated. The rules must apply to everyone, and no exceptions.  Of course it is  his right to choose  not to be vaccinated but he must accept the consequences of that choice, and accept he can not play in the Australian Open unvaccinated.  If he wants to play next year at the tournament,  then, unless the rules have changed by then,  he must be vaccinated.   Tough luck for him, but since he is one of the richest people on the planet,  he will not suffer, at least financially, by being excluded from this year’s Australian open.
He is certainly one of the greatest tennis players ever and no one would doubt his talent. Unfortunately his manner and behavior do not live up to his greatness and a player and frankly, if he does not attend, he will not be missed by many, with the exception of Serbs living in Melbourne. 
The 2 other great players of our time, Nadal and Federer,  are much more likable people and more popular,  and if either man won this year’s Open, 
He would certainly get a great and warm reception from the audience at the court, or from the public in general in Australia.  The same can not be said for Djokovic  -  and it would do the game a lot of good if any other player, whether Federer, Nadal, or anyone else,  wins the Australian Open this year.
